{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474242"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:18:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:18:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11897"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11897","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11897"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.25,0.03,0.32,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4494"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43805"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4494"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11897"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28794"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3949"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6603"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6607"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20593"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43805"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old football player is bought in by ambulance to the Emergency Department directly from his game with a cervical collar in place. During the game, the patient was tackled and, with his arms pinned by his side, dropped down directly onto the top of his head, resulting in axial compression. The patient did not lose consciousness, however experienced immediate and severe neck pain. The patient is able to recount the experience fully and his day prior to the incident. On examination, there is no evidence of sensation changes and he is able to move all of his extremities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following fracture is the patient most at risk of?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Odontoid fracture","Hangman fracture","Boxer\u0027s fracture","Jefferson fracture","Monteggia fracture"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA Jefferson fracture\u003C/strong\u003E is also known as a C1 burst fracture and results from an axial loading force that is transmitted through the occipital condyles to the superior articular surfaces of the lateral masses of the first cervical vertebra (C1). It is considered an unstable fracture and 40% have associated C2 fractures. On plain radiograph, it is best seen on the open-mouth odontoid view as the lateral masses are shifted laterally. It is associated with diving accidents, \u201cspearing\u201d in contact sport, direct force to the top of the head and other injuries in which there is an increased axial load to the cervical spine. Diagnosis is often missed with plain radiographs so a CT scan may be required to make the diagnosis. An open-mouth odontoid radiograph is useful to evaluate for disruption of the transverse ligament which leads to lateral displacement of the lateral masses relative to each other.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOdontoid fractures \u003C/strong\u003Eoccur when there is a fracture through the odontoid process of the C2 vertebra, and it is considered an unstable cervical fracture. it is frequently as a result of hyperextension of the neck, commonly seen in low energy falls in elderly patients and high energy traumatic injuries in younger patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA Hangman\u0027s fracture\u003C/strong\u003E (traumatic spondylolysis of C2) occurs when the cervico-cranium is thrown into extreme hyperextension secondary to abrupt deceleration (e. head-on high impact car accidents, hangings). This is also an unstable cervical fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA Boxer\u0027s fracture \u003C/strong\u003Eis a fracture of the 5th metacarpal bone and often results from punching something with sufficient force.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA Monteggia fracture-dislocation\u003C/strong\u003E refers to a dislocation of the radial head with associated proximal 1/3 ulna fracture. It is more common in the paediatric population and can occur from a direct blow to posterior elbow, hyper-pronated force on an outstretched arm or when a contracted biceps resists forearm extension causing dislocation and followed by impact leading to ulna fracture\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Jefferson Fractures (C1 burst fractures) are traumatic injuries usually caused by high-energy trauma with axial loading in young patients or low-energy falls in elderly.","Jefferson fractures usually present with neck pain without neurological features due to capacious nature of the spinal canal at this level"],"references":["Mead LB, Millhouse PW, Krystal J, et al. C1 fractures: a review of diagnoses, management options, and outcomes. Curr Rev Musculoskelet Med 2016: 9:255\u201362"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28794"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11897"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28794"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-27T20:42:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-03-27T20:42:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4494"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43805"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"